June 6th, 1899:

It requires consistent flesh sacrifices to continue operation at full capacity, not a surprise but a difficulty if we plan to take this to Mexico. I've instructed my legwork to use livestock and the occasional drunkard, although I am not afraid to turn to more unconventional methods. 

My experiment with the corpse has come along well.  It has been far too long since I have modified FLESH, and Fordham has proven himself particularly useful. He was the one who provided me with my tasting module, introducing me to the delectable and biting taste of blood coffee, and much to my luck, the aforementioned coffee shop provided just what I sought.  

I have taken much joy in arming this new automaton. This has been an excellent medium by which I can test the capabilities of the stomach. Through several of the lamb sacrifices, we've obtained some incredibly valuable components, and through those components have come new constructs. 

My best work thus far is the replacement for the corpse's left arm, an incredibly powerful tool operated as follows. 

* Users attach their fingers to a subject's teeth. 
* The fingers then inject a fast-acting calcium compound into the subject's bones.
* Once the subject's bones are hardened, the hydraulics in the mechanical arm activate, allowing the user to separate the subject's bones from their FLESH. 


 When we are brought new sacrifices, we shall use this to split the corpses we receive into specific parts, allowing us to better optimize the outcomes of our sacrifices.  

This new automaton will be perfect. A figure so divine and faultless that it will disgrace any other construct assembled by the hands of man. 

June 8th, 1899: 

Damn it all to hell. If it weren't for these imbecilic meatheads, we would've been back in Mexico by now. 

We're being followed. Our more covert intelligence have inserted themselves across businesses in the area.  One of them, inserted in a bar, managed to get one of the local constables to blabber about the <a style='color:#630700' href="https://scp-wiki.wikidot.com/scp-8712">livestock disappearances</a>. A private detective by the name of Sherlock Holmes and his oafish sidekick, John Watson, are investigating the case and are likely the cause of the rats' disappearances. Fordham says he might be able to construct a technology from the stomach that will allow me to keep a constant eye on our agents. 

In the interim, I have instructed Brogly to find a way to infect Holmes with our new <a style='color:#630700' href="https://scp-wiki.wikidot.com/scp-217">biological sample </a>. I am not going to let this officious FLESH sack throw himself in the way of my destiny. 

This will be dealt with swiftly. Apotheosis shall be achieved, no matter the cost.
]]

