**Manifest 226:** Clara Greene's Account. Dated June 14th, 1899.

A report delivered to Her Majesty's Foundation on the actions of Dr. John H. Watson and Sherlock Holmes regarding AO-8712.
-----

**07:48 HOURS:**
Dr. Watson leaves his residence on Baker Street clutching the golden letter the church delivered yesterday. I feared I would have to step in like I did at the scrapyard, but thankfully he appeared armed. 

**09:22 HOURS:** 
I took a back route to the hotel and arrived shortly before the doctor. Rather than darting directly for the stairs as I expected, he spent a moment in the lobby to listen for Tickers, a pleasant surprise. I trailed him as he made his way to room 346, a journey made difficult by his insistence to inspect every door frame he passed. 

Eventually, he arrived at the room, and to my dismay, he entered with little hesitation. I brought my eye to the peephole and watched as the warped shape of the doctor entered the room. Somehow, the church had managed to choose the one hotel with walls thicker than an inch. As such, it was difficult for me to make out anything they were saying.

The form of the Schematist was difficult to discern. He had positioned himself in such a way that the sunlight obscured his appearance. I held out hope that Watson would realize the room was a trap, that he would hear the ticking, or realize the Schematist had no flesh, or that he would trust his gut instinct, yet they just kept talking. 

Watson sluggishly shuffled before the Schematist, careful to keep his grip on his revolver. The Schematist's hands shifted about, a movement that alarmed Watson as he unloaded a bullet into the Schematist's temple. 

In a blink, Watson found himself pinned to the wall, the Schematist's metal fingers quickly enclosing his throat. 

I pulled, twisted, and jerked the doorknob to no result before resorting to throwing my shoulder in the door in a futile attempt to get it to budge. My attempts were all for nothing as I found myself on the floor as Watson's body crashed through the doorway. He groaned, certainly having shattered a few bones. I scrambled to my feet, watching as the Schematist retrieved a canister I had become disgustingly familiar with. 

I pulled Watson to his feet. "By Jove, you're the dame from the scrapyard!" he bellowed. 

I nodded, explaining the urgency with which we needed to evacuate the hotel. Together, we limped down the stairs. Before arriving in the lobby, we were met with the sound of ticking clockwork. 

"They're waiting for us..." Watson gasped as I swore under my breath.

Watson pulled his firearm from his jacket. 

"I'm taking you hostage." Watson illustrated. 

"Excuse me?" 

He knocked on his shoulder; the metal rang out. "They'll think I'm one of them." 

I understood our mission. Watson held his revolver to my temple, and together we walked through the lobby, then stopped. 

"Sorry sir, the hotel's under quarantine. I'm going to have to ask you to head back to your room." A man approached us, the sounds of clockwork beneath his skin louder than that of a grandfather clock. A peer into the gaping hole where his left eye once was revealed hundreds of tiny gears. 

"I'm taking this woman back to the warehouse, Schematist's orders." Watson knocked on his shoulder again. The dumb prats bought his story, and we made our way out of the hotel. 

**10:33 HOURS:**

We attempted to travel back to Baker Street to regroup with Holmes. Much to our dismay every corner we turned held another occultist. We resorted to alleyways for our progression, yet even then we had to adjust our path several times. I was thankful that Watson was so familiar with the layout of the city as I surely would have led us to our demise. 

"It's as though they've abducted half of the city." Watson gasped for air as we took a short break in an alleyway garden. 

"They're being chalked up to disappearances, I'm sure you know that..." I explained, "But I'm not sure how long we can keep this charade up."

"Not to worry." He exclaimed, "This will all be over soon and we shall be allowed to return to our normal lives."

He helped me to my feet and we continued to make passage for Baker Street. 

**11:25 HOURS:**

Eventually, we took refuge in Grosvenor Square, despite the time, it was just as empty as the rest of London. 

"So you're the madam who's been stalking my home?" Watson inquired. 

When I asked how he knew that, he explained the cigarettes that were found in the gutter outside his home each morning, a sizable oversight on my part. 

We exchanged our notes, Watson had amassed a sizable documentation of the church's activity, hundreds of cold hard facts we had overseen in our speculation regarding the anomalous object. Together, our documentation provided more than enough information for me to present to my superiors to justify mobilization against the church. 

Watson asked me how soon we could raid the warehouse, claiming his fear for his life and his wife's. I saw right through him; he was seeking revenge for what happened to Holmes and for his injuries. 

I explained it would take a couple of days to reach approval for this sort of action, but I would let him know when it happens. Soon, we parted ways, and I made my return to Charles Street. 

Watson is clearly disturbed by the church's ideals of eternal life, and the condition of his friend has shaken him to his core. He is an incredibly brave man, but it's clear he is terrified, as expected from someone's first interaction with the unconventional. I believe with time, he could be a valuable asset to our organization. 

Take this as my request that, once the situation dies down, Dr. Watson sees counseling rather than amnestic treatment. 
